Ask HN: Is remote going away? Why?
text:
I hear stories around me and it seems like the remote is ebbing atm.

More and more companies are cutting down on it increasing the needed presence. At the same time they just don't have the real estate capacity to do it decently which means (at least in my personal experience) that you land in a noisy subpar open space (worst invention ever) for n days a week where you can hardly do any work.

Not to mention wasting time/energy in commuting.

It really beats me why a company would waste resources like that and I cannot explain it. The best I have is that this is some kind of power play but I'm not convinced. Am I missing something?

Show HN: AssetSpace – new fixed asset management tool
text:
Hello guys and gals! Your honest feedback is needed more than ever! We've just launched AssetSpace - a tool designed to help small and mid-size offices take control of their fixed assets like laptops, printers, coffee machines, and pretty much any other office stuff - https://assetspace.org/.

Easier than complex systems out there but handier than a spreadsheet, our system includes key features like: Asset Library & Tracking, Customized categories & groups, QR-code Creation & Scanning, Entire tracking history of asset events, Various filters, Roles & rights management

And more to come! Especially since we've tried to create an intuitive tool that can evolve along with users' needs. By the way, all core features are available within the Free plan.

All your comments, feedback, and ideas for future improvements are more than welcome! We're noting!

Ask HN: How much of inflation is caused by supply rather than demand issues?
text: The Fed’s rates increases are predicated on the belief that they will “tame inflation.”  But Fed representatives recognize it’s a blunt instrument, which in particular won’t address supply side issues, which are impacting, e.g., the price of gas and food.  A major decision to raise rates so quickly is (certainly?) based on research and deliberation.  I’d imagine that the Fed concluded that, while the instrument is blunt, it’s better than any alternatives.  Could someone help explain the extent to which the Fed actually has the power to tame this current bout of inflation—whether their efforts have a ceiling, if you will—and what alternatives it might have considered, but discarded?
